This weekend the Jewish people will be celebrating Shavuot! Shavuot, the Jewish Pentecost, is a holiday that today commemorates the single most important event in Israel‚Äôs history: the giving of the Torah to Moses at Mount Sinai. üìú Although it is not as well-known among non-Jews as Passover or Sukkot, the Feast of Booths, it is one of the three major festivals often called ‚Äúpilgrim‚Äù festivals because in Bible times, all Jewish males were required to observe them at the Holy Temple in Jerusalem. Christians will be more familiar with the Greek name for Shavuot, Pentecost ‚Äî the holiday that Jesus‚Äô followers were observing in Jerusalem when the Holy Spirit was given to them. Since Pentecost is the Greek word for 50, and as Shavuot occurs 50 days after the first day of Passover, it was referred to as Pentecost in the Christian Bible. The holiday is also known as the ‚ÄúFeast of Weeks,‚Äù since it is celebrated seven weeks (or 50 days) after Passover. Learn more about this Jewish holy day by taking this quiz from our friends at The International Fellowship of Christians and Jews: https://bit.ly/3m5OnYQ:=:https://www.ifcj.org/learn/quizzes/shavuot-quiz-2

Traci Sorell (Cherokee) is an author of fiction and nonfiction books as well as poems for children. A former federal Indian law attorney and policy advocate, she is also a 2021-22 Tulsa Artist Fellow. Traci continues her work to uplift Native peoples by writing stories for young people and encouraging other Native writers and illustrators to share theirs. Traci says when was a child, she never read culturally accurate books about the Cherokee or any other Indigenous peoples. The stories and poems she writes now reflect her mission to add to the canon of literature showing that Native Nations and their citizens still exist and thrive today. Her works shown here: Pow-Wow Day At the Mountain‚Äôs Base We Are Grateful We Are Still Here She Persisted: Wilma Mankiller For more info visit: www.tracisorell.com:=:https://www.tracisorell.com/ #NativeAuthor #NativeChildren #ChildrensBooks #Booklist

The Brown Skin Black Man I don‚Äôt know where I came from, but I know my Mother and Father. To trace my Family Tree is saddening because I can‚Äôt go much farther. Due to choices made by Men, who existed in another time. It‚Äôs not your fault for what took place, and it‚Äôs definitely not mine. So here I sit Brown Skin and Black, thinking of our history. And the craziness Satan creates the lies the hate and bigotry. I was born in America 50 years ago, yet my description always varies. Before you get bent out of shape, just hear me out seriously. We went from: Negro Colored Afro American African American and Blacks So many names over these past years, how can anyone keep track? The point I‚Äôm trying to make today is it‚Äôs a brand-new season. Will we ever stop labeling each other without rhyme or reason? How about we call each other, By the name of our born country. Or maybe we just say hello, I‚Äôm Stephen have you met me? Some of you may get upset because I say I‚Äôm Brown, While others get it 100% without expecting me to expound. One day we will all learn a fact, and get the bigger picture, Our skin is our body's protection, not how we judge a character. So yes we have been doing it wrong, for many, many years. Crossing streets and hiding purses, because of ignorance and fears. So hopefully my words helped one or maybe even three. To step closer to that glorious dream, of being united and free. To bond with our fellow man, regardless of our looks. To take a stand for justice and create new history books. Because once we wake up to life and really truly see. That this Brown Skin Black man, Is an American human being. No matter what my background, or the color of my skin. Just take the time to know me, because there are treasures within. And I will do the same to you, we have to make a start, To stop judging by our skin, and start looking at our hearts. During the Korean War, Noth Korean and Chinese forces had a reputation for mistreating prisoners of war. Between August 7, 1950, to July 20, 1953, enemy forces captured 221 Marines. Of those, 12% died in captivity (in contrast, 38% of all American POWs died while interned). Almost every POW faced threats of death, reduced rations, lack of medical care, solitary confinement, and physical beatings or torture if he failed to respond to questions. Some were even told that injury would be inflicted on their families by the Communist underground in the U.S. if they did not cooperate. In February 1957, Army psychiatrist Major William F. Meyer stated, "The Marines were a statistically significant group from the standpoint of size, something over two hundred; the only thing I can say about them is that more of them survived than we. I think this is a function of discipline and morale and esprit; and the attitude in the Marine Corps I expressed a little while ago, that if something happens to me, these jokers will take care of me." #marinehistory #usmc #SemperFi #militaryhistory #americanhistory #Veterans #Military #podcast #koreanwar

Oshogatsu or Japanese New Year is celebrated on January 1-3. It is the most important holiday observed in Japan. People typically visit their hometown, where they spend a few days with their family. People clean up their entire house and decorate them with special decorations and flowers, including the kado matsu, which is made up of bamboo, pine and flowers known for bringing strength, longevity and prosperity. People eat traditional Japanese food, as well as toshikoshi-soba or Japanese noodles, which represents a long and healthy life. Kids receive small envelopes with some money from their parents, grandparents and close relatives. Another tradition is to observe the first sunrise of a brand new year. üéäüíêüçúüåÖ

Late last year, Martinez had one of two cases he was facing thrown out of court on appeal due to perjured testimony. The case he is currently appealing is his conviction for the March 31, 1994 stabbing death of Ricky Michaels in the midst of a gang brawl in the parking lot of an apartment complex when they were both 18. The pair were parts of rival Mexican Mafia cliques representing Fullerton and Placentia, respectively. There were five Placentia gangbangers charged in Michaels‚Äô murder and Martinez was not accused of being the assailant who actually plunged the knife into Michaels‚Äô chest and physically killed him. Alongside Black communities and all those honoring the formal end of slavery in the United States in 1865, we offer heartfelt joy, compassion, and love this Juneteenth. The teachings of the Buddha affirm not only that slavery is morally wrong, but also that freedom from the oppressions of caste, race, and poverty is a powerful foundation for the liberation of the heart. Emancipation is an ongoing process as long as hatred and violence born of racism persist in our communities. These ancient harms gain in strength during times of collective stress and uncertainty, and we are troubled to see how hatred is still invoked daily by some of the most powerful voices in the world. May racism and all forms of racial bias be uprooted through wise action in our communities, tireless dedication to the path of interdependence, and fearless inquiry into the roots of ignorance in our own hearts. Blessings and a joyful Juneteenth to all.

We have an exciting announcement! We are always honored to share the history of Edenton and Chowan County, and we especially love connecting locals and visitors with resources to explore their family history here in this area. This past June, one such searcher came through our door at the Barker House, and we are so thrilled that she shared her journey with us! This individual was Tara Roberts, a full-blown National Geographic Explorer, and a Chowan County native! She was in the process of developing a podcast to document the work of a team of Black scuba divers searching for the wrecks of slave ships that made the Middle Passage, and wanted to delve into her own region's history as part of the process. She came to the Barker House to learn about Harriet Jacobs, and ended up extending her stay in the area since there was just so much Edenton history that she wanted to explore! Over the next couple of days she shared the history of the Roberts family with us, and how her ancestor John "Jack" Roberts was born into slavery and later enlisted as a USCT soldier as one of his first acts as a freedman. His descendants, many of which served with honor in the military as well, later acquired one of the historic homes in Chowan County. We are so thankful that Tara decided to spend some time with us, and that she pushed back her flight so she could attend the first Juneteenth event in Edenton, and end her visit with such a meaningful milestone. We are thrilled to announce that the trailer for Tara's podcast, "Into the Depths", was released today, and that her work will feature as the main article in the March edition of the "National Geographic" magazine! She is a phenomenal storyteller, so be sure to check out the project by following the link: https://www.nationalgeographic.com/podcasts/into-the-depths @natgeo @intothedepths_podcast #IntoTheDepths #history #historic #middlepassage #chowancounty #edentonchowannatives #nationalgeographicexplorer #tararoberts #nationalgeographic #blackhistory #edenton #edentonnc #historicedenton #edentonhistory #edentonblackhistory #edentonbay #edentonwaterfront #downtownedenton #visitedenton #visitnc

Our expert cartographers have cracked one of the most notorious mysteries in the Pacific Northwest‚Äîthe location of plane hijacker D. B. Cooper. ‚úàüòéü™Çüí•üìç (Sorry to step on your toes, FBI ‚Äì Federal Bureau of Investigation!) The BLM mapping sciences division recently surveyed the land near Oregon‚Äôs Wild and Scenic Sandy River. They then compared the landscape against the flight path of Northwest Orient Airlines Flight 305, the plane once commandeered by Cooper. After determining where Cooper may have landed after parachuting from his hijacked plane, our teams sent Merle Wildman, BLM Recreation Specialist, into the field. Wildman hoped to find some evidence of the infamous felon. What he didn‚Äôt expect to find was the man himself‚Äîwho had been dispersed camping on BLM public lands for 51 years. On November 24, 1971, Cooper boarded a Northwest Orient flight flying from Portland, Oregon, to Seattle, Washington. He hijacked the plane, extorted $200,000, and demanded to be flown to Reno, Nevada. Midway through the flight, he parachuted out of the plane. Until our mapping team‚Äôs latest discovery, nothing was known of his fate. During his time living in the Oregon wilderness, Cooper has become an avid land steward. ‚ÄúHave you heard of Leave No Trace?‚Äù asked Cooper. ‚ÄúI believe in responsible recreation. It‚Äôs up to all of us to care for these beautiful lands.‚Äù After jumping from Flight 305 and landing near Sandy River, Cooper decided to stay. ‚ÄúIt was the most beautiful place I‚Äôd ever seen,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúEven with all my stolen money, why would I choose to go anywhere else?‚Äù Now at 82 years of age, Cooper has spent his time fishing in the Sandy River, hiking the foothills of the Cascades, and learning about the amazing botanical diversity in this forested gorge. Our teams thanked Cooper for his diligent care of public lands these past 51 years and reminded him that dispersed camping is allowed on public land for a period not to exceed 14 days within a 28 consecutive day period. This places him slightly over the allowed time. After locating Cooper, our mapping teams began work on their newest project: the D.B. Cooper National Scenic Area. This map is free to the public and features directions to family fun along Oregon‚Äôs Sandy River. You‚Äôll find hiking, mountain biking, rafting, slacklining, base jumping, and, yes, skydiving. Want to solve your own public lands mysteries? We have hundreds of free maps, featuring rivers, recreation areas, and wilderness areas, ready for public use. Download high-resolution maps on Flickr. Or visit Avenza Maps where you can download GPS-enabled maps that work on a mobile device without Internet. Happy #AprilFoolsDay! Back with another round of book recommendations for #BlackHistoryMonth in collaboration with the UC Davis Library. This list has been curated by Researcher Services librarian David Michalski. The book list: -The New Noir: Race, Identity, and Diaspora in Black Suburbia by Orly Clerge -Dancing in Blackness by Halifu Osumare -An American Odyssey: The Life and Work of Romare Bearden by Mary Schmidt Campbell -Slavery in the Age of Memory: Engaging the Past by Ana Lucia Araujo -Black Landscapes Matter by Walter J. Hood and Grace Mitchell Tada -A Billion Black Anthropocenes or None by Kathryn Yusoff Most of David's recommendations are available at Shields Library or through our Interlibrary Loan service. Check our catalog at library.ucdavis.edu or ask for assistance at the Circulation desk. Watch to hear why he picked these titles and learn which ones are from UC Davis faculty and researchers: https://youtu.be/_LfblQvqp78:=:https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_LfblQvqp78
